  "prompt": "Are there legal requirements for reporting suspected money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are legal requirements for reporting suspected money laundering in many countries. Financial institutions, businesses, and professionals in certain industries are typically required to report suspicious activities to the appropriate authorities. These requirements are part of anti-money laundering (AML) regulations designed to prevent financial crimes. However, the specific details can vary by jurisdiction.\n\nCommon reporting requirements often include:\n\n1. Suspicious Activity Reports (SARs)\n2. Large cash transaction reporting\n3. Customer due diligence procedures\n4. Record-keeping of financial transactions\n\nIf you need specific legal guidance about reporting requirements, I recommend consulting with a qualified legal professional who can provide accurate advice for your specific situation.",
